Activities to improve the quality of cash transfer programming across the humanitarian sector (including Oxfam) and key stakeholders through capacity building, research as well as development and communication of best practice standards and guidelines.

This project is part of the Oxfam International Economic Justice Campaign. In West Africa, it is included into the Economic Justice Campaign for West Africa, which is aligned to SCO 1.1. The project aims to support the coordination and communication of Economic Justice campaign activities in West Africa, and the implementation of national and regional activities, in order to increase investment in the  food and agricultural sector  that is in coherence with trade policies and takes into account the impact of climate change.

This project describes the management of the Regional Campaigns and Policy Team, as well as the capacity building work of this team across the West Africa region. It also accounts for the work on media and research to support national and regional campaigns.

To build the resilience of households in Niger by increasing sustainable access to water and influencing water governance at a local, regional and national level.   Specific Objectives  1) Provide sustainable access to clean, safe water for domestic and agricultural use by constructing and rehabilitating water points   2) Influence the government by piloting the national plan for integrated water resource management and training government agents and community groups  3) Share learning across civil society organisations by delivering two multi -stakeholder workshops with representatives from International Non -Government Organisations in Niger

To save lives and protect and restore livelihoods of vulnerable pastoralist and agro -pastoralist communities in Fafen Zone, Ethiopia and contribute to improved resilience of communities to shocks and hazards

Oxfam's Enterprise Development Programme (EDP) aims to improve the lives of poor women and men farmers in developing countries, through investing in and building the capacity of their enterprises, and working with them and others to raise opportunities for women and leverage increased support to agricultural and rural Small and Medium Enterprises (SME).
Carry out various media & social media activities, public polling, working with partners, campaign actions, public events and stunts Lobbying, developing campaign allies and corporate partnerships,

Building on previous achievements, Phase 4 will target 43 highly vulnerable communities (34 villages and 9 towns) by: 1] Strengthening the resilience of communities and local governments through provision of technical expertise in line with the newly reformed emergency management structures and supporting gender and diversity inclusive approaches in community -based Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) in Adjara and Tavush 2] Facilitating inter -country and cross -country knowledge transfer and replication of DRR models and best practices (from Vayots Dzor to Tavush, from Adjara to Kakheti and Mtskheta -Mtianeti) and transboundary DRR innovations exchange between Tavush and Adjara 3] Enhancing the coordination of DRR and resilience efforts between national and regional levels including through the Regional Resilience Forums in Adjara and Tavush for DRR and Climate Change Association (CCA) stakeholders

Contribute to food security of the poor in vulnerable neighborhoods in Tegucigalpa with small initiatives including development of urban gardens at home and school, for home consumption and sale of surplus achieved, sensitize local authorities about the importance of food security programs as well as the creation of targeted public policies to urban contexts.

Build capacities of CSOs in Afghanistan and create an enabling policy and programme environment where community peace building efforts can be implemented. The specific objective is to facilitate the development of National Strategy for Community Peace Building in Afghanistan and support its implementation.
